The `runMain(main)` error is telling us that the effect we’re handing to `runMain` still has an unresolved environment (`R = unknown`). `runMain` only accepts effects whose environment has already been reduced to `never`, so TypeScript refuses the call.

How this happens:

- `runtimeLayer` is built with `Layer.mergeAll(...)` and (after the logger export problem is fixed) each `Live` layer should supply all of its own dependencies. But because we manually call `Layer.build(runtimeLayer)` and then push the resulting context into `Effect.provide(context)`, TypeScript can’t prove that every requirement is satisfied—`Layer.build` returns an effect with an `unknown` environment, and piping it through `Effect.scoped` still leaves `R = unknown`.
- The structured log stack trace you pasted (`effect(missingEffectContext)`) is the library’s way of warning that we’re trying to run an Effect that still expects some service.

What we’ll need to do to clear this:

1. Fix the barrel exports first. TypeScript is still complaining that `LoggerLive` isn’t exported (`apps/server/src/main.ts:5`), so it never makes it to the later stages. Once `@ci-dashboard/platform-logger` actually re-exports `LoggerLive`/`withRequestId`, we can revisit the environment problem.
2. Rewire `main` so the environment truly closes before calling `runMain`. Two easy patterns, either of which will make the typechecker happy:
   - Provide the layer instead of manually building it:  
     ```ts
     const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
       yield* runMigrations;
       yield* runBackfillScheduler;
       yield* startReconciler;
       const config = yield* Config;
       yield* Effect.logInfo(`server boot on port ${config.port}`);
       return yield* Effect.never;
     }).pipe(
       Effect.provideLayer(runtimeLayer),
       Effect.scoped
     );

     runMain(program);
     ```
     Here `Effect.provideLayer` does the bookkeeping so `R` becomes `never`.
   - Or keep the current structure but pin the types:  
     ```ts
     const runtimeLayer: Layer.Layer<never, never, never> = Layer.mergeAll(...);
     ```
     This tells TypeScript that the layer really leaves no environment requirements. If it’s wrong, compilation will fail and we’ll see which dependency is missing.

Either way we’re making the type system aware that `main`’s environment is fully satisfied. After that the `runMain` call stops complaining.

Once those two pieces are in place, rerun `pnpm exec tsc -p apps/server/tsconfig.json --noEmit`; it should finally progress to the remaining errors (there are still missing imports and partially written files elsewhere, but this unblocks the `runMain` failure specifically).

